The complete information about the restriction(s), actually held in handbooks or other publications, may be encoded by the attribute 'TXTDSC'. A short explanation may be given by the use of the attribute 'INFORM'.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: anchoring prohibited
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: an area within which anchoring is not permitted.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: anchoring restricted
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: a specified area designated by appropriate authority, within which anchoring is restricted in accordance with certain specified conditions.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: fishing prohibited
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: an area within which fishing is not permitted.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: fishing restricted
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: a specified area designated by appropriate authority, within which fishing is restricted in accordance with certain specified conditions.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: trawling prohibited
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: an area within which trawling is not permitted.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: trawling restricted
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: a specified area designated by appropriate authority, within which trawling is restricted in accordance with certain specified conditions.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: entry prohibited
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: an area within which navigation and/or anchoring is prohibited.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: entry restricted
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: a specified area designated by appropriate authority, within which navigation is restricted in accordance with certain specified conditions.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: dredging prohibited
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: an area within which dredging is not permitted.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: dredging restricted
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: a specified area designated by appropriate authority, within which dredging is restricted in accordance with certain specified conditions.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: diving prohibited
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: an area within which diving is not permitted.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: diving restricted
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: a specified area designated by appropriate authority, within which diving is restricted in accordance with certain specified conditions.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: no wake
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: mariners must adjust the speed of their vessels to reduce the wave or wash which may cause erosion or disturb moored vessels.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: area to be avoided
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: an IMO designated area to be avoided, defined as a routeing measure.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: construction prohibited
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: the erection of permanent or temporary fixed structures or artificial islands is prohibited.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: discharging prohibited
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: an area within which discharging or dumping is prohibited

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: discharging restricted
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: a specified area designated by an appropriate authority, within which discharging or dumping is restricted in accordance with specified conditions.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: industrial or mineral exploration/development prohibited
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: an area within which industrial or mineral exploration and development are prohibited.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: industrial or mineral exploration/development restricted
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: a specified area designated by an appropriate authority, within which industrial or mineral exploration and development is restricted in accordance with certain specified conditions.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: drilling prohibited
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: an area within which excavating a hole on the sea-bottom with a drill is prohibited.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: drilling restricted
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: a specified area designated by an appropriate authority, within which excavating a hole on the sea-bottom with a drill is restricted in accordance with certain specified conditions.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: removal of historical artifacts prohibited
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: an area within which the removal of historical artifacts is prohibited.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: cargo transhipment (lightering) prohibited
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: an area in which cargo transhipment (lightering) is prohibited.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: dragging prohibited
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: an area in which the dragging of anything along the bottom, e.g. bottom trawling, is prohibited.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: stopping prohibited
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: an area in which a vessel is prohibited from stopping.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: landing prohibited
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: an area in which landing is prohibited.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: speed restricted
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: an area within which speed is restricted.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: swimming Prohibited
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: an area in which swimming is prohibited.

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Scale maximum
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: The maximum scale at which the object may be used, e.g., for ECDIS presentation.
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:remarks: The modulus of the scale is indicated, that is 1:25 000 is encoded as 25000.

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Scale minimum
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: The minimum scale at which the object may be used, e.g., for ECDIS presentation.
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:remarks: The modulus of the scale is indicated, that is 1:1 250 000 is encoded as 1250000.

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Sector limit one
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: The sector limit 1 specifies the first limit of the sector. The order of sector limit 1 and sector limit 2 is clockwise around the central object (e.g., a light).
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:remarks: A sector is the part of a circle between two straight lines drawn from the centre to the circumference (Advanced Learner's Dictionary, 2nd Edition). The values given to the common limits of adjacent sectors should be identical. The orientation of bearing is from seaward to the central object. This conforms with the method used in 'List of Lights' publications. A generic term such as 'to shore' cannot be used; a specific bearing must be encoded. Where a light sector limit is defined as 'to the shore', it should be encoded using a value that ensures that, when the limit is drawn, it will fall entirely on land.

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Sector limit two
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: The sector limit 2 specifies the second limit of the sector. The order of sector limit 1 and sector limit 2 is clockwise around the central object (e.g., a light).
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:remarks: A sector is the part of a circle between two straight lines drawn from the centre to the circumference (Advanced Learner's Dictionary, 2nd Edition). The values given to the common limits of adjacent sectors should be identical. The orientation of bearing is from seaward to the central object. This to the method used in 'List of Lights' publications. A generic term such as 'to shore' cannot be used; a specific bearing must be encoded. Where a light sector limit is defined as 'to the shore', it should be encoded using a value that ensures that, when the limit is drawn, it will fall entirely on land.

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Signal frequency
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: The frequency of a signal.

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Signal generation
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: The mechanism used to generate a fog signal.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: automatically
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: signal generation is initiated by a self regulating mechanism such as a timer or light sensor.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: by wave action
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: the signal is generated by the motion of the sea surface such as a bell in a buoy.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: by hand
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: the signal is generated by a manually operated mechanism such as a hand cranked siren.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: by wind
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: the signal is generated by the motion of air such as a wind driven whistle.

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Signal group
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: The number of signals, the combination of signals or the morse character(s) within one period of full sequence.

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Signal period
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: The time occupied by an entire cycle of intervals of light and eclipse.

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Status
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: The condition of an object at a given instant in time

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: permanent
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: intended to last or function indefinitely.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: occasional
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: acting on special occasions happening irregularly.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: recommended
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: presented as worthy of confidence, acceptance, use, etc.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: not in use
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: no longer used for the purpose intended disused.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: periodic/intermittent
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: recurring at intervals.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: reserved
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: set apart for some specific use.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: temporary
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: meant to last only for a time.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: private
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: not in public ownership or operation.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: mandatory
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: compulsory enforced.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: extinguished
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: no longer lit

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: illuminated
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: lit by floodlights, strip lights, etc.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: historic
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: famous in history of historical interest.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: public
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: belonging to, available to, used or shared by, the community as a whole and not restricted to private use.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: synchronized
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: occur at a time, coincide in point of time, be contemporary or simultaneous.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: watched
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: looked at or observed over a period of time especially so as to be aware of any movement or change.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: un-watched
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: usually automatic in operation, without any permanently-stationed personnel to superintend it.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: existence doubtful
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: an object that has been reported but has not been definitely determined to exist.

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Surrounding depth
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: The depth value determined for seabed around an underwater hazard of unknown depth, based on the depth of the surrounding area.

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Survey authority
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: The authority which was responsible for the survey.
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:remarks: The attribute 'survey authority' encodes the name of the source survey authority.(Example: Hydrographic Service, Royal Australian Navy Port of Melbourne Authority)

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Survey type
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: Classification of the diffrent survey types

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: reconnaissance/sketch survey
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: a survey made to a lower degree of accuracy and detail than the chosen scale would normally indicate.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: controlled survey
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: a thorough survey usually conducted with reference to guidelines.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: examination survey
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: a survey principally aimed at the investigation of underwater obstructions and dangers.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: passage survey
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: a survey where soundings are acquired by vessels on passage.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: remotely sensed
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: a survey where features have been positioned and delimited using remote sensing techniques.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: full coverage
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: a survey achieving 100% coverage using systematic, controlled techniques providing full seafloor coverage or full coverage to a defined depth and an investigation of all contacts.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: systematic survey
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: a controlled survey but full coverage may not have been achieved.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: non-systematic survey
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: a survey of lower quality than a full coverage and systematic survey. Such surveys may be further categorised as reconnaissance, sketch, track, passage, remotely sensed and spot-sounding surveys.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: inadequately surveyed
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: a survey that is not to modern standards, or which, due to its age, scale, or positional or vertical uncertainties is not suitable to the type of navigation expected in the area.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: spot-sounding survey
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: a survey that uses a regular (e.g. grid) or irregular pattern of soundings obtained one at a time, and normally with very wide spacing.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: acoustically swept survey
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: a controlled, systematic survey to standard accuracy; using modern survey echo sounder with sonar sweep.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: mechanically swept survey
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: swept areas where the clearance depth is accurately known but the actual seabed depth is not accurately known.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: found by echo-sounder
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: The depth was measured by using an instrument that determines depth of water by measuring the time interval between emission of a sonic or ultrasonic signal and return of its echo from the seabed.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: found by side scan sonar
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: The depth was computed from a record produced by active sonar in which fixed acoustic beams are directed into the water perpendicularly to the direction of travel to scan the seabed and generate a record of the seabed configuration.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: found by multi-beam
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: The depth was measured by using a wide swath echo sounder that uses multiple beams to measure depths directly below and transverse to the ship's track.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: found by diver
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: The depth was measured by a person skilled in the practice of diving.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: found by lead-line
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: The depth was measured by using a line, graduated with attached marks and fastened to a sounding lead.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: swept by wire-drag
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: The given area was determined to be free from navigational dangers to a certain depth by towing a buoyed wire at the desired depth by two launches, or a least depth was identified using the same technique.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: found by laser
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: The elevation was measured by using an instrument that measures distance by emitting timed pulses of laser light and measuring the time between emission and reception of the reflected pulses.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: swept by vertical acoustic system
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: The given area has been swept using a system comprised of multiple echo sounder transducers attached to booms deployed from the survey vessel.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: found by electromagnetic sensor
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: The depth was measured by using an instrument that compares electromagnetic signals.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: photogrammetry
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: The depth was determined by applying mathematical techniques to photographs.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: satellite imagery
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: The depth was determined by using instruments placed aboard an artificial satellite.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: found by levelling
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: The depth was measured by using levelling techniques to find the elevation of the point relative to a datum.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: swept by side-scan sonar
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: The given area was determined to be free from navigational dangers to a certain depth by towing a side-scan-sonar.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: found by LIDAR
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: The depth was measured by using an instrument that measures distance by emitting timed pulses of laser light and measuring the time between emission and reception of the reflected pulses.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: left
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: the anchor point is at the start of the text string.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: centred
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: the anchor point is at the centre of the text string.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: right
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: the anchor point is at the end of the text string.

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Text type
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: The attribute from which a text string is derived.

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Time end
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: The end of a active period.

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Time start
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: The start of an active period.

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Topmark/daymark shape
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: The shape a topmark or day mark exhibits

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: cone, point up
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: is where the vertex points up. A cone is a solid figure generated by straight lines drawn from a fixed point (the vertex) to a circle in a plane not containing the vertex. Cones are commonly used as International Association of Lighthouse Authorities - IALA topmarks lateral.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: cone, point down
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: is where the vertex points down. A cone is a solid figure generated by straight lines drawn from a fixed point (the vertex) to a circle in a plane not containing the vertex. Cones are commonly used as International Association of Lighthouse Authorities - IALA topmarks lateral.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: sphere
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: a body the surface of which is at all points equidistant from the centre. Spheres are commonly used as International Association of Lighthouse Authorities - IALA topmarks safe water.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: 2 spheres
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: two black spheres are commonly used as an International Association of Lighthouse Authorities - IALA topmark (isolated danger).

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: cylinder (can)
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: a solid geometrical figure generated by straight lines fixed in direction and describing with one of point a closed curve, especially a circle (in which case the figure is circular cylinder, it's ends being parallel circles). Cylinders are commonly used as International Association of Lighthouse Authorities - IALA topmarks lateral.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: board
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: usually of rectangular shape, made from timber or metal and used to provide a contrast with the natural background of a daymark. The actual daymark is often painted on to this board.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: x-shape (St. Andrew's cross)
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: having a shape or a cross-section like the capital letter X. An x-shape as an International Association of Lighthouse Authorities - IALA topmark should be 3 dimensional in shape. It is made of at least three crossed bars.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: upright cross (St. George's Cross)
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: a cross with one vertical member and one horizontal member, i.e. similar in shape to the character '+'.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: cube, point up
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: a cube standing on one of its vertexes. A cube is a solid contained by six equal squares a regular hexahedron (The New Shorter Oxford English Dictionary. 1993. vol 2)

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: 2 cones, point to point
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: 2 cones, one above the other, with their vertices together in the centre.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: 2 cones, base to base
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: 2 cones, one above the other, with their bases together in the centre and their vertices pointing up and down.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: rhombus
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: a plane figure having four equal sides and equal opposite angles (two acute and two obtuse) an oblique equilateral parallelogram.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: 2 cones (points upward)
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: 2 cones, one above the other, with their vertices pointing up.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: 2 cones (points downward)
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: 2 cones, one above the other, with their vertices pointing down.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: besom, point up (broom or perch)
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: besom: a bundle of rods or twigs. perch: a staff placed on top of a buoy, rock or shoal as a mark for navigation.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: besom, point down (broom or perch)
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: besom: a bundle of rods or twigs. perch: a staff placed on top of a buoy, rock or shoal as a mark for navigation.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: flag
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: a flag mounted on a short pole.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: sphere over rhombus
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A sphere located above a rhombus.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: square
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: a plane figure with four right angles and four equal straight sides

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: rectangle, horizontal
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: a rectangle is a plane figure with four right angles and four straight sides, opposite sides being parallel and equal in length . A horizontal rectangle is where the two longer opposite sides are standing horizontally.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: rectangle, vertical
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: a rectangle is a plane figure with four right angles and four straight sides, opposite sides being parallel and equal in length. A vertical rectangle is where the two longer opposite sides are standing vertically.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: trapezium, up
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: which stands on its longer parallel side. A trapezium is a quadrilateral having one pair of opposite sides parallel.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: trapezium, down
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: which stands on its shorter parallel side. A trapezium is a quadrilateral having one pair of opposite sides parallel.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: triangle, point up
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A triangle, point up. A triangle is a figure having three angles and three sides.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: triangle, point down
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A triangle, point down. A triangle is a figure having three angles and three sides.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: circle
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: a perfectly round plane figure whose circumference is everywhere equidistant from its centre.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: two upright crosses (one over the other)
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: two upright crosses, generally vertically disposed one above the other.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: T-shape
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: having a shape like the capital letter T.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: triangle pointing up over a circle
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: a triangle, vertex uppermost, located above a circle.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: upright cross over a circle
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: an upright cross located above a circle.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: rhombus over a circle
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: a rhombus located above a circle.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: circle over a triangle pointing up
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: a circle located over a triangle, vertex uppermost.

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Traffic flow
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:remarks: The direction of travel

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: inbound
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: traffic flow in a general direction toward a port or similar destination.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: outbound
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: traffic flow in a general direction away from a port or similar point of origin.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: one-way
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: traffic flow in one general direction only.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: two-way
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: traffic flow in two generally opposite directions.

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Value of annual change in magnetic variation
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: The annual change in magnetic variation values.
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:remarks: A positive value, i.e., unsigned, indicates a change in an easterly direction and a negative value indicates a change in a westerly direction. Distinguished from 'value of magnetic variation'.

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Value of depth contour
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: The depth of a sea bottom contour.
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:remarks: Drying contours are indicated by a negative value. The unit of measure is defined in the DUNI subfield of the DSPM record or in the DUNITS attribute of the M_UNIT meta object class, e.g., metre (m). The resolution is 0.1 m or 0.1 fm or 0.1 ft.

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Value of magnetic variation
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: The magnetic variation value.
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:remarks: A positive value, i.e., unsigned, indicates variation in an easterly direction and a negative value indicates variation in a westerly direction. Distinguished from 'value of annual change in magnetic variation'.

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Value of maximum range
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: The extreme distance at which an object can be seen or a signal detected.
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:remarks: This attribute does not apply to lights where the attribute 'value of nominal range' should be used.

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Value of nominal range
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: The nominal range at which an object can be seen or a signal detected.
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:remarks: The nominal range is normally the luminous range of a light in a homogeneous atmosphere in which the meteorological visibility is 10 sea miles (IHO Hydrographic Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 4218).

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Value of sounding
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: The value of the measurement of a sounding relative to the chart datum.
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:remarks: A drying height is indicated by a negative value. The unit of measure is defined in the DUNI subfield of the DSPM record or in the DUNITS attribute of the M_UNIT meta object class, e.g., metre (m). The resolution is 0.1 m or 0.1 fm or 0.1 ft.

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Vertical clearance value
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: The vertical clearance measured from the plane towards the object overhead.
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:remarks: In the case of cables carrying high voltages an additional clearance of from 2 to 5 metres may be needed to avoid an electrical discharge. When known, the authorized safe clearance (known in the UK as the Safe Overhead Clearance) which is the physical clearance minus a safety margin shall be stated (IHO Chart Specifications, M-4). See also 'vertical clearance safe'. The unit of measure is defined in the HUNI subfield of the DSPM record or in the HUNITS attribute of the M_UNIT meta object class, e.g., metre (m). The resolution is 0.1 m or 0.1 ft.

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Vertical datum
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: Vertical datum used for measuring elevations of points on the earth's surface. Its the datum to which both heights and soundings are referred.
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:remarks: When the vertical datum is unknown, such as water areas above locks, the value 'local datum' is to be used, and further details may be encoded using 'INFORM'. The +0.3m approximation quoted in the 'approximate' levels is somehow arbitrary and follows the British example of their definition for 'approximate LAT'.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: mean low water springs
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: (MLWS) - the average height of the low waters of spring tides.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: mean lower low water springs
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: (MLLWS) - the average height of lower low water springs at a place.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: mean sea level
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: (MSL) - the average height of the surface of the sea at a tide station for all stages of the tide over a 19-year period, usually determined from hourly height readings measured from a fixed predetermined reference level.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: lowest low water
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: an arbitrary level conforming to the lowest tide observed at a place, or some what lower.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: mean low water
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: (MLW) - the average height of all low waters at a place over a 19-year period.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: lowest low water springs
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: an arbitrary level conforming to the lowest water level observed at a place at spring tides during a period of time shorter than 19 years.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: approximate mean low water springs
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: an arbitrary level, usually within ' 0.3m from that of mean low water springs (MLWS).

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Indian spring low water
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: (ISLW) - an arbitrary tidal datum approximating the level of the mean of the lower low water at spring tides.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: low water springs
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: an arbitrary level, approximating that of mean low water springs (MLWS).

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: approximate lowest astronomical tide
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: an arbitrary level, usually within ' 0.3m from that of lowest astronomical tide (LAT).

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: nearly lowest low water
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: an arbitrary level approximating the lowest water level observed at a place, usually equivalent to the Indian spring low water (ISLW).

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: mean lower low water
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: (MLLW) - the average height of the lower low waters at a place over a 19-year period.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: low water
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: an approximation of mean low water adopted as the reference level for a limited area, irrespective of better determinations at a later date.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: approximate mean low water
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: an arbitrary level, usually within ' 0.3m from that of mean low water (MLW).

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: approximate mean lower low water
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: an arbitrary level, usually within ' 0.3m from that of mean lower low water (MLLW).

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: mean high water
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: (MHW) - the average height of all high waters at a place over a 19-year period.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: mean high water springs
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: (MHWS) - the average height of the high waters of spring tides.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: high water
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: the highest level reached at a place by the water surface in one tidal cycle.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: approximate mean sea level
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: an arbitrary level, usually within ' 0.3m from that of mean sea level (MSL).

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: high water springs
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: an arbitrary level, approximating that of mean high water springs (MHWS).

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: mean higher high water
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: (MHHW) - the average height of higher high waters at a place over a 19-year period.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: equinoctial spring low water
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: the level of low water springs near the time of an equinox.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: lowest astronomical tide
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: (LAT) - the lowest tide level which can be predicted to occur under average meterological conditions and under any combination of astronomical conditions.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: local datum
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: an arbitrary datum defined by a local harbour authority, from which levels and tidal heights are measured by this authority.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: international great lakes datum 1985
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: (IGLD 1985) - a vertical reference system with its zero based on the mean water level at Rimouski/Pointe-au-P??re, Quebec, over the period 1970 to 1988.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: mean water level
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: the average of all hourly water levels over the available period of record.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: lower low water large tide
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: (LLWLT) - the average of the lowest low waters, one from each of 19 years of observations.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: higher high water large tide
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: (HHWLT) - the average of the highest high waters, one from each of 19 years of observations.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: nearly highest high water
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: an arbitrary level approximating the highest water level observed at a place, usually equivalent to the high water springs.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: highest astronomical tide (HAT)
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: the highest tidal level which can be predicted to occur under average meteorological conditions and under any combination of astronomical conditions.

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Vertical length
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: The total vertical length of an object.
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:remarks: For floating objects: the vertical distance from the surface of water to the highest point of that object. For fixed objects: the vertical distance from seabed or ground to the highest point of that object. For objects on top of other objects: the vertical distance from the lowest to the highest point of that object. Vertical length measurements do not require a datum. The unit of measure is defined in the HUNI subfield of the DSPM record or in the HUNITS attribute of the M_UNIT meta object class, e.g., metre (m). The resolution is 0.1 m or 0.1 ft.

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Vertical uncertainty
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: The best estimate of the vertical accuracy of heights, vertical distances and vertical clearances, excluding sounding measurements. The one-dimensional error. The error is assumed to be positive and negative. The plus/minus character shall not be encoded.
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:remarks: The unit of measure is defined in the HUNI subfield of the DSPM record or in the HUNITS attribute of the M_UNIT meta object class, e.g., metre (m). The resolution is 0.1 m or 0.1 ft.

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Virtual AIS aid to navigation type
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: A purpose of a virtual AIS Aid to navigation.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: visually conspicuous
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: term applied to an object either natural or artificial which is distinctly and notably visible from seaward.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: prominent
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: an object which is visible from seaward and may be used as a fixing mark, but is not conspicuous.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: not visually conspicuous
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: an object which is visible from seaward, but is not conspicuous.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: partly submerged at high water
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: partially covered and partially dry at high water.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: always dry
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: not covered at high water under average meteorological conditions.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: always under water/submerged
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: remains covered by water at all times under average meteorological conditions.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: covers and uncovers
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: expression intended to indicate an area of a reef or other projection from the bottom of a body of water which periodically extends above and is submerged below the surface. Also referred to as 'dries or uncovers'.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: awash
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: flush with, or washed by the waves at low water under average meteorological conditions.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: subject to inundation or flooding
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: an area periodically covered by flood water, excluding tidal waters.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: floating
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: resting or moving on the surface of a liquid without sinking

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Communication information
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: The complex attribute provides the contact details for ships requiring pilotage services through one or more communication methods.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Current velocity
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: The complex attribute encodes the range of the velocity of a tidal or non-tidal current.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Directional character
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: The complex attribute defines whether the light is a moir? effect light and encodes the orientation of the directional light sector.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Feature name
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: The complex attribute provides the name of an entity, defines the national language of the name, and provides the option to display the name at various system display settings.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Features Detected
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: The uniform assessment of detected features.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Fixed date range
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: The complex attribute describes single fixed period, as the date range between its sub-attributes.
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:remarks: the sub-attributes date start and date end must be encoded using 4 digits for the calendar year (YYYY) and, optionally, 2 digits for the month (MM) (e.g. April = 04) and 2 digits for the day (DD). When no specific month and/or day is required/known, the values are replaced with dashes (-).

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Horizontal clearance fixed
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: The complex attribute encodes the horizontal distance

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Horizontal clearance open
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: The complex attribute encodes the horizontal distance

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Information
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: The complex attribute provides additional textual information that cannot be provided using other allowable attributes for the feature, and defines the language of the text string.
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:remarks: this complex attribute should be used, for example, to hold the information that is shown on paper charts by cautionary and explanatory notes.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Light sector
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: A sector is the part of a circle between two straight lines drawn from the centre to the circumference. (Advanced Learner's Dictionary, 2nd Edition).

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Measured distance value
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: The distance value indicated on a distance mark, or the distance between two measured distance marks.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Multiplicity of features
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: The complex attribute provides an indication as to whether the true number of features is known and, where known, the number of features.
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:remarks: the attribute multiplicity of features must only be used to indicate the number of entities of a feature that are co-located (e.g. 3 overhead cables suspended over a body of water between 2 pylons), and this information is considered to be of use to the mariner. Where possible, features must be encoded individually.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Orientation
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: The angular distance measured from true north to the major axis of the feature.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Periodic date range
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: The complex attribute describes the active period for a seasonal feature (e.g. a buoy), as the dates between its sub-attributes.
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:remarks: the sub-attributes date start and date end should be encoded using 4 digits for the calendar year (YYYY),2 digits for the month (MM) (e.g. April = 04) and 2 digits for the day (DD). When no specific year is required(i.e. the feature is removed at the same time each year) the following two cases may be considered: - same day each year: ----MMDD - same month each year: ----MM-- This conforms to ISO 8601:2004.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Radar wave length
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: The complex attribute describes the wave length, as the combination of its sub-attributes.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Rhythm of light
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: The complex attribute describes the rhythm of a light (or a light sector).

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Sector characteristics
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: The complex attribute describes the characteristics of a light sector.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Sector information
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: The complex attribute provides additional textual information that cannot be provided using other allowable attributes for the feature, and defines the language of the text string.
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:remarks: this complex attribute should be used, for example, to hold the information related to the characteristics of a complex light sector.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Sector limit
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: The complex attribute describes the angle of a light sector as defined by the subattributes.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Shape information
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: The complex attribute provides additional textual information that cannot be provided using the attribute topmark/daymark shape.
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:remarks: no formatting of text is possible within shape information. If formatted text is required, then an associated text file referenced by the complex attribute textual description must be used (see clause X.X).

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Signal sequence
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: The complex attribute provides the signal sequence for non-fixed lights.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Surface characteristics
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: The general nature of the material of which the land surface or the seabed is composed.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Survey date range
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: The complex attribute describes the period of the hydrographic survey, as the time between its sub-attributes.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Textual description
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: The complex attribute encodes the file name of a single external text file that contains the text in a defined language, which provides additional textual information that cannot be provided using other allowable attributes for the feature.
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:remarks: the complex attribute is generally used for long text strings or those that require formatting, however, there is no restriction on the type of text (except for lexical level) that can be held in files referenced by subattribute file reference.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Tidal stream panel values
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: The direction of the flow and the springs rate from 6 hours before to 6 hours after high water (HW) or low water (LW) at the reference tide station, at hourly or sub-hourly intervals.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Tidal stream value
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: A measurement of the direction and velocity of a tidal stream at a given time relative to the reference tide.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Time range
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: The complex attribute describes the active time period of an event (e.g. a bridge opening time), as the time between its sub-attributes.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Topmark
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: A characteristic shape secured at the top of a buoy or beacon to aid in its identification.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Update description
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: The complex attribute provides additional textual information describing changes made to an ENC dataset resulting from application of an ENC Update.
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:remarks: the sub-attribute text is populated with a brief description of the changes made when the Update is applied, e.g.: Navigational aids inserted Changes to depths alongside and new pontoons added

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Value of local magnetic anomaly
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: The complex attribute encodes the range of the local magnetic anomaly.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Vertical clearance closed
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: The complex attribute encodes the vertical distance from a defined vertical datum to the underside of a an opening overhead feature when it is in the closed position.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Vertical clearance fixed
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: The complex attribute encodes the vertical distance from a defined vertical datum to the underside of a fixed overhead feature.
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:remarks: in the case of cables carrying high voltages an additional clearance of from 2 to 5 metres may be needed to avoid an electrical discharge. When known, the authorised safe clearance (known in the UK as the Safe Overhead Clearance) which is the physical clearance minus a safety margin shall be stated, using the attribute vertical clearance safe (see clause X.X). vertical clearance fixed must not be used to populate authorized safe clearances.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Vertical clearance open
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: The complex attribute encodes the vertical distance from a defined vertical datum to the underside of a an opening overhead feature when it is in the open position.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Vertical clearance safe
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: The complex attribute encodes the safe vertical distance from a defined vertical datum to the lowest point of an electrical cable over navigable water.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Vessel speed limit
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: The complex attribute describes the speed limit for vessels in an area where speed is restricted.
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:remarks: the speed limit in an area may differ for different classes of vessel.

S100FC:S100_FC_Role.S100FC:name: Provides
S100FC:S100_FC_Role.S100FC:definition: acts as the authority and provider of a specified service.

S100FC:S100_FC_Role.S100FC:name: Supported by
S100FC:S100_FC_Role.S100FC:definition: a pointer to the master feature that equipment feature(s) are supported by.

S100FC:S100_FC_Role.S100FC:name: Supports
S100FC:S100_FC_Role.S100FC:definition: a pointer to the equipment feature(s) supported by a master feature.

S100FC:S100_FC_Role.S100FC:name: Component of
S100FC:S100_FC_Role.S100FC:definition: a pointer to a part in a whole-part relationship.

S100FC:S100_FC_Role.S100FC:name: Consists of
S100FC:S100_FC_Role.S100FC:definition: a pointer to the aggregate in a whole-part relationship.

S100FC:S100_FC_Role.S100FC:name: Boarding location
S100FC:S100_FC_Role.S100FC:definition: a location where a pilot may board.

S100FC:S100_FC_Role.S100FC:name: Identifies
S100FC:S100_FC_Role.S100FC:definition: a pointer to a specific feature(s).

S100FC:S100_FC_InformationAssociation.S100FC:name: Additional information
S100FC:S100_FC_InformationAssociation.S100FC:definition: an information association for the binding between at least one instance of a geo feature and an instance of an information type.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.S100FC:name: ASL aggregation
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.S100FC:definition: a feature association for the binding between an Archipelagic Sea Lane and its component features.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.S100FC:name: Structure/equipment
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.S100FC:definition: a feature association for the binding between a navigation aid equipment feature and the structure that supports it.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.S100FC:remarks: valid structure and equipment features are listed in clause X.X.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.S100FC:name: Aids to navigation association
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.S100FC:definition: a feature association for the binding between navigational aids and the traffic systems (such as routeing measures) that they define.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.S100FC:name: Bridge aggregation
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.S100FC:definition: feature association for the binding between a bridge and its component features.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.S100FC:remarks: a bridge over non-navigable water at the maximum display scale of the ENC data, which does not require its individual components to be encoded, must be encoded, where required, as a Bridge feature of type curve or surface (see clause X.X).

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.S100FC:name: Bridge association
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.S100FC:definition: a feature association for the binding between a bridge and equipment features on the bridge (e.g. lights).

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.S100FC:name: Caution area association
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.S100FC:definition: a feature association for the binding between a caution area and the traffic systems (such as routeing measures) to which the cautionary information applies.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.S100FC:name: Deep Water route aggregation
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.S100FC:definition: a feature association for the binding between a Deep Water route and its component features.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.S100FC:name: District boarding locations
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.S100FC:definition: The binding between a pilotage district and the pilot

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.S100FC:name: Island aggregation
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.S100FC:definition: a feature association for the binding between a named group if islands.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.S100FC:name: Range system aggregation
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.S100FC:definition: a feature association for the binding between navigational tracks and the navigational aids that define the tracks.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.S100FC:name: Traffic Separation Scheme aggregation
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.S100FC:definition: a feature association for the binding between a Traffic Separation Scheme or a Traffic Separation Scheme System and its component features.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.S100FC:name: Two-way route aggregation
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureAssociation.S100FC:definition: a feature association for the binding between a two-way route and its component features.

S100FC:S100_FC_InformationType.S100FC:name: Supplementary information
S100FC:S100_FC_InformationType.S100FC:definition: Information about a feature or a number of features additional to that able to be encoded using other feature attributes.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Data coverage
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A geographical area that describes the coverage and extent of spatial types.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Navigational system of marks
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An area within which a specific system of navigational marks applies and/or a common direction of buoyage.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Sounding datum
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An area of uniform sounding datum.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Vertical datum of data
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: Any level surface from which to reference elevations. Also called datum level, reference level, reference plane, levelling datum, datum for heights.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Quality of survey
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An area within which a uniform assessment of the reliability of source survey information exists.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Magnetic variation
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: The angle between the magnetic and geographic (true) north at a location, expressed in degrees east or west from the direction of true north.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Local magnetic anomaly
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An anomaly of the magnetic field of the Earth, extending over a relatively small area, due to local magnetic influences.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Coastline
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: The line where shore and water meet. Although the terminology of coasts and shores is rather confused, shoreline and Coastline are generally used as synonyms.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Land area
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: The solid portion of the Earth's surface, as opposed to sea, water.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Land elevation
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An elevation is the vertical distance of a point or a level, on, or affixed to, the surface of the earth, measured from a specified vertical datum.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: This object class is used to encode both spot heights and land (height) contours.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: River
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A relatively large natural stream of water.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: The object 'river' describes the area of the river, the object 'river bank' its banks.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Rapids
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: Portions of a stream with accelerated current where it descends rapidly but without a break in the slope of the bed sufficient to form a waterfall. Usually used in the plural.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Waterfall
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A sudden descent of water over a step in the bed of a river.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: In place names commonly shortened to fall or falls, e.g. Niagara Falls.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Lake
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A large body of water entirely surrounded by land.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Land region
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An area of natural scenery on land. It is defined by its geographical characteristics and may be known by its proper name.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Vegetation
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: Collections of, or individual plants.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Ice area
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An area of ice over land or water.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Sloping ground
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An inclined surface.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Slope topline
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: The upper marking of a slope, e.g. the ridge line or the separation line between two different gradients.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Tideway
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A natural water course in intertidal areas where water flows during the ebb or flow.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: A channel through which a tidal current runs.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Built-up area
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An area containing a concentration of buildings and the supporting road or rail infrastructure.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Building
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A relatively permanent structure, roofed and usually walled. It is designed for some particular use which it may be important to indicate.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: This object class is used to encode single buildings, including those with a particular function or service of major interest.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Airport/airfield
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An area containing at least one runway, used for landing, take-off, and movement of aircraft.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Runway
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A defined rectangular area, on a land aerodrome, prepared for the landing and take-off run of aircraft along its length.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: A site on which helicopters may land and take off (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 2232).

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Bridge
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A structure erected over a depression or an obstacle such as a body of water, railroad, etc. to provide a roadway for vehicles, pedestrians or to carry utility services.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: A bridge may consist of portions which cover the land and the water.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Conveyor
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A mechanical apparatus for moving bulk material or people from place to place (as by a moving belt or chain of receptacles).

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Cable, overhead
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An overhead cable is an assembly of wires or fibres, or a wire rope or chain, which is supported by structures such as poles or pylons and passing over or nearby navigable waters.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: The cable supports are encoded as pylon/bridge supports (PYLONS).

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Pipeline, overhead
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An overhead pipeline is a pipeline supported by pylons and passing over or nearby navigable waters.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: A pipeline is a string of interconnected pipes used for the transport of matter, nowadays mainly oil or gas (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 3857).

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Pylon/bridge support
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A vertical construction consisting, for example, of a steel framework or pre-stressed concrete to carry cables, a bridge, etc.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Fence/Wall
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A natural or man-made barrier used as an enclosure or boundary or for protection.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Railway
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A rail or set of parallel rails on which a train or tram runs.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Road
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A road is an open way for the passage of vehicles.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Tunnel
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A passage that is open to the atmosphere at both ends, buried under the sea bed or laid over the sea floor or bored under the ground or through mountains.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Landmark
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A prominent object at a fixed location which can be used in determining a location or a direction.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Silo/tank
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An enclosed container, used for storage.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Fortified structure
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A structure for the military defence of a site.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: A fortified structure is often disused, decayed or used for non-defence purpose. Such structures range from major castles and forts to minor lookout posts.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Production/storage area
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An area on land for the exploitation or storage of natural resources.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Checkpoint
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An official place to register, declare or check goods and people.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: The object 'checkpoint' does not include facilities such as buildings, gates or other installations.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Hulk
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A permanently moored ship.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Pile
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A long heavy timber or section of steel, wood, concrete, etc. forced into the earth which may serve as a support, as for a pier, or a free standing pole within a marine environment.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Dyke
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A dyke (or dike) is an artificial embankment to contain or hold back water.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Shoreline construction
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A fixed (not afloat) artificial structure between the water and the land, i.e. a man-made Coastline.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Causeway
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A raised way across low or wet ground or water.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Canal
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An artificial waterway with no flow, or a controlled flow, used for navigation, or for draining or irrigating land (ditch).
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: The object 'canal' describes the area of the canal, the object 'canal bank' describes the banks.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Distance mark
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A distance mark indicates the distance measured from an origin and consists of either a solid visible structure or a distinct location without special installation.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: Usually found on canals.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Gate
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A structure that may be swung, drawn, or lowered to block an entrance or passageway.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: This object class is used to encode gates that control the flow of water.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Dam
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A barrier to check or confine anything in motion; particularly one constructed to hold back water and raise its level to form a reservoir, or to prevent flooding.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Crane
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A machine for lifting, shifting and lowering objects or materials by means of a swinging boom or with a lifting apparatus supported on an overhead track.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: The position of a sheerlegs or a travelling crane is defined as its resting position.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Berth
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A named or numbered place where a vessel is moored at a wharf.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Mooring/Warping facility
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: The equipment or structure used to secure a vessel.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Dry dock
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An artificial basin fitted with a gate or caisson, into which vessels can be floated and the water pumped out to expose the vessel's bottom.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Floating dock
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A form of dry dock consisting of a floating structure of one or more sections which can be partly submerged by controlled flooding to receive a vessel, then raised by pumping out the water so that the vessel's bottom can be exposed.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Pontoon
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A floating structure, usually rectangular in shape which serves as landing, pier head or bridge support.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Dock area
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A dock is an artificially enclosed area within which ships may moor and which may have gates to regulate water level.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Gridiron
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A structure in the intertidal zone serving as a support for vessels at low stages of the tide to permit work on the exposed portion of the vessel's hull.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: Also called 'careening grid'.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Lock basin
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A lock basin is a wet dock in a waterway, permitting a ship to pass from one level to another.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Sea area/named water area
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A geographically defined part of the sea or other navigable waters. It may be specified within its limits by its proper name.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: Each sea area is defined independent of any other. Smaller sea areas may be located within larger sea areas.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Tidal stream - flood/ebb
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: Approximate tidal stream rates given as discrete rate values for flood and ebb flow during springs.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: A tidal stream (or tidal current) is a horizontal movement of water associated with the rise and fall of the tide caused by tide-producing forces (adapted from IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition).

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Current - non-gravitational
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: Currents (non-gravitational) include either singly or in combination: ocean currents (wind and/or density driven), inter-oceanic equalising currents, currents of navigable rivers, river outflow effects offshore and other non-tidal flows.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Water turbulence
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: The disturbance of water caused by the interaction of any combination of waves, currents, tidal streams, wind, shoal patches and obstructions.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Tidal stream panel data
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: Approximate tidal stream rates given as discrete rate values at a specified interval before or after a high water.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: A tidal stream (or tidal current) is an alternating horizontal movement of water associated with the rise and fall of the tide caused by tide-producing forces (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 1169). The object 'tidal stream panel data' encodes data for use in a tidal panel.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Sounding
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A measured water depth or spot which has been reduced to a vertical datum (may be a drying height).
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: Drying heights (drying soundings) are indicated by a negative value.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Dredged area
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An area of the bottom of a body of water which has been deepened by dredging.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Swept Area
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An area that has been determined to be clear of navigational dangers to a specified depth.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Depth contour
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A line connecting points of equal water depth which is sometimes significantly displaced outside of soundings, symbols and other chart detail for clarity as well as generalization.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: Depth contours, therefore, often represent an approximate location of the line of equal depth as related to the surveyed line delineated on the source. Also referred to as depth curve. Drying contours are encoded with negative values.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Depth area
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A depth area is a water area whose depth is within a defined range of values.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: Intertidal areas are encoded as depth areas. These do not have to include soundings. The depth range within a depth area is defined by the attributes DRVAL1 and DRVAL2.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Unsurveyed area
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An area for which no bathymetric survey information is available.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Seabed area
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An area of the sea where the nature of bottom is homogeneous. The nature of bottom includes the material of which it is composed and its physical characteristics.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: Generally, it is not possible to define a seabed area by its real extent. For that reason, the characteristics of the seabed area may be represented at one single position.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Weed/Kelp
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: Seaweed, any macroscopic marine alge or seagrass (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 4589). Kelp is one of an order (laminariales) of usually large, blade-shaped or vine-like brown algae (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 2611).
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: Seaweed is the general name for marine plants of the Algae class which grow in long narrow ribbons (International Maritime Dictionary, 2nd Ed.). Kelp is often an indication of the presence of submerged rocks (IHO Chart Specifications M-4).

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Sand waves
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A large mobile wave-like sediment feature in shallow water and composed of sand. The wavelength may reach 100 metres, the amplitude may be up to 20 metres.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Spring
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A natural issue of water or other substances from the earth. One on the bottom of the sea is called a 'submarine spring'.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Underwater/awash rock
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A concreted mass of stony material or coral which dries, is awash or is below the water surface.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Wreck
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: The ruined remains of a stranded or sunken vessel which has been rendered useless.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Obstruction
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: In marine navigation, anything that hinders or prevents movement, particularly anything that endangers or prevents passage of a vessel.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: The term is usually used to refer to an isolated danger to navigation.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Fishing facility
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A structure in shallow water for fishing purposes which can be an obstruction to ships in general.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: The position of these structures may vary frequently over time.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Marine farm/culture
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An assemblage of cages, nets, rafts and floats or posts where fish, including shellfish, are artificially cultivated.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Offshore platform
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A permanent offshore structure, either fixed or floating, used in the production of oil or natural gas.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Cable, submarine
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An assembly of wires or fibres, or a wire rope or chain which has been laid underwater or buried beneath the seabed.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Cable area
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An area which contains one or more submarine cables.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Pipeline, submarine/on land
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A submarine or land pipeline is a pipeline lying on or buried under the seabed or the land.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: A pipeline is a string of interconnected pipes used for the transport of matter, nowadays mainly oil or gas (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 3857). It must be assumed that the pipes are vulnerable to damage from anchoring or trawling. They may be a potential danger to navigation (IHO Chart Specifications, M-4).

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Submarine pipeline area
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An area containing one or more pipelines.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Offshore production area
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An area at sea within which there are production facilities.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Navigation line
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A navigation line is a straight line extending towards an area of navigational interest and generally generated by two navigational aids or one navigational aid and a bearing.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: The extent of the navigation line depends on the visibility of the navigational aid(s). The attribute 'orientation' (ORIENT) specifies the orientation of the navigation line measured from the water towards the navigational aid(s). The recommended track is that portion of a 'navigation line' that a ship should use for navigation.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Recommended track
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A track recommended to all or only certain vessels.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: Recommended tracks include all channels recommended for hydrographic reasons to lead safely between shoal depths. The use of such tracks is generally left to the discretion of the mariner and will depend on the vessel's draught, the state of the tide, adequacy of navigational aids and so on (IHO Chart Specifications, M-4). The recommended track is that portion of a 'navigation line' that a ship should use for navigation. In the case of a two-way recommended track only one value of orientation is encoded (in the attribute ORIENT); the other value can be deduced (i.e. the value in ORIENT + 180 degrees).

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Fairway
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: That part of a river, harbour and so on, where the main navigable channel for vessels of larger size lies.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: It is also the usual course followed by vessels entering or leaving harbours, called 'ship channel'.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Recommended route centerline
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A recommended route centerline indicates the 'centerline' of a recommended route.
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:remarks: A recommended route is a route of undefined width, for the convenience of ships in transit, which is often marked by centerline buoys (IHO Dictionary, S-32, 5th Edition, 4448). A recommended route describes the regulation of navigation for non-hydrographic reasons such as the prevention of collision or the avoidance of pollution risks. It is generally laid down by a national or international authority other than the hydrographic authority. (IHO Chart Specifications, M-4)

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Two-way route part
